          <h2>Introduction: Why Maintenance and Collimation Matter</h2>
          <p>Telescope performance depends critically on two factors: optical quality (determined at manufacture) and optical alignment (your responsibility as owner). Even the finest telescope optics—hand-figured mirrors costing thousands of dollars—deliver poor performance when misaligned or poorly maintained. Conversely, budget optics properly collimated and cared for can outperform expensive equipment neglected by owners who assume "set and forget" applies to telescopes.</p>

          <p>Collimation—the precise alignment of optical elements along a common axis—determines whether your telescope achieves its theoretical performance limits. Misaligned optics scatter light, reduce contrast, soften fine detail, and create asymmetric star images. A 6-inch Newtonian with perfect collimation will show crisper planetary detail and sharper star images than an 8-inch Newtonian with poor collimation, despite the latter's larger aperture. Collimation affects all telescope types but most critically impacts Newtonians which use mirrors mounted in adjustable cells that shift from vibration, temperature changes, and transport.</p>

          <p>Beyond collimation, routine maintenance preserves your telescope's optical and mechanical quality for decades. Proper cleaning techniques prevent coating damage that degrades light transmission and contrast. Dew prevention stops moisture from spotting optics and corroding metal components. Correct storage prevents fungus growth on optics, dust accumulation, and mechanical wear. Simple maintenance practices—occupying perhaps 30 minutes monthly—protect equipment investments ranging from hundreds to tens of thousands of dollars while ensuring peak performance every observing session.</p>

