          <h2>Collimation Theory: Understanding Optical Alignment</h2>
          <p>Collimation aligns all optical elements (lenses, mirrors, eyepiece focuser) so light travels along the telescope's optical axis without deviation. When perfectly collimated, light from a star enters the tube, reflects from mirrors or refracts through lenses along precisely calculated paths, and converges at the focal plane creating a diffraction-limited point image. Misalignment causes light to converge at wrong angles, creating aberrated images with reduced sharpness and contrast.</p>

          <h3>The Diffraction-Limited Image</h3>
          <p>Perfect optics with perfect collimation produce diffraction-limited images determined solely by aperture and physics—these show point sources (stars) as tiny disks (Airy disks) surrounded by concentric diffraction rings. A 6-inch telescope at 150x displays stars as 0.76 arcsecond disks surrounded by progressively dimmer rings containing 16%, 7%, and 3% of the star's light. Atmospheric turbulence typically prevents achieving this theoretical performance, but good collimation gets you close. Poor collimation scatters light from the Airy disk into surrounding rings and space, dimming the star, reducing contrast, and softening planetary detail.</p>

          <h3>Why Newtonians Require Frequent Collimation</h3>
          <p>Newtonian reflectors use two mirrors mounted in adjustable cells: the parabolic primary mirror at the tube's base and the flat secondary mirror suspended near the top by spider vanes. Both require precise alignment. The secondary reflects incoming light 90 degrees toward the focuser; the primary focuses this light to a point at the eyepiece. These mirrors must align perfectly along the optical axis—any tilt or offset degrades performance.</p>

          <p>Unfortunately, Newtonian mechanics work against collimation stability. Primary mirrors sit in cells adjusted by three or six screws (collimation bolts) that owners can turn, but these screws can also drift from vibration during transport. Secondary mirrors mount on tiltable platforms secured by three adjustment screws—these too can shift. Temperature changes cause metal components to expand and contract at different rates, altering alignment. Simply moving a Dobsonian from storage to observing site can disturb collimation enough to degrade performance noticeably.</p>

          <p>Fast focal ratio Newtonians (f/4-f/5) are even more collimation-sensitive than slow systems (f/6-f/8). An f/4 Newtonian showing misalignment of 1mm at the secondary produces dramatically worse optical effects than the same 1mm offset in an f/8 system. This explains why fast Dobsonians popular for deep sky observing require frequent collimation checks while slow astrophotography Newtonians may hold collimation for weeks.</p>

          <h3>Refractor and SCT Collimation Stability</h3>
          <p>Refractors use lenses mounted in sealed cells with no user-adjustable components (generally). Lens elements are permanently aligned at factory and remain stable for the telescope's lifetime unless subjected to severe mechanical shock. This explains refractors' reputation for being "set and forget"—they simply don't lose collimation through normal use. Premium refractors may include objective cell adjustment screws for expert users, but most manufacturers advise against touching these without professional training.</p>

          <p>SCTs (Schmidt-Cassegrain Telescopes) fall between Newtonians and refractors for collimation stability. The primary mirror is fixed at the rear of the tube and rarely requires adjustment. Only the secondary mirror (mounted on the corrector plate's interior) needs periodic collimation using three adjustment screws accessible from the front. SCT collimation typically remains stable for weeks to months, degrading only gradually from thermal expansion, vibration, and transport. Many SCT users never collimate after initial factory setup if the telescope remains permanently mounted on an observatory pier.</p>
        </section>

