          <h2>Newtonian Collimation: Step-by-Step Procedure</h2>
          <p>Collimating a Newtonian reflector involves aligning both the secondary and primary mirrors sequentially. The process requires 3-5 minutes once mastered and should become routine before every observing session. You'll need either a laser collimator ($30-$80) or Cheshire eyepiece ($20-$40), plus a sight tube for secondary adjustment.</p>

          <h3>Tools Required</h3>
          <p><strong>Laser Collimator:</strong> Projects laser beam down optical axis. When properly collimated, laser reflects from primary mirror back to illuminate the collimator's entrance aperture. Provides fast, convenient alignment but requires the laser itself be precisely manufactured (cheap lasers may have off-axis beams). Popular models: Celestron laser collimator ($35), Astro Baby laser ($45), Howie Glatter ($80-$120 with graduated circles for precision).</p>

          <p><strong>Cheshire Eyepiece:</strong> Tube with crosshairs and 45-degree viewing window that illuminates the optical path. Allows direct viewing of mirror reflections for precise alignment. Many experts prefer Cheshires for final precision work. Popular models: Celestron Cheshire ($25), Astro-Tech Cheshire ($30), William Optics Cheshire ($40).</p>

          <p><strong>Sight Tube (Collimation Cap):</strong> Simple tube with centered hole for viewing down optical axis. Often included free with telescopes. DIY versions made from film canisters with centered pins work well. Used primarily for rough secondary alignment.</p>

          <h3>Step 1: Secondary Mirror Alignment</h3>
          <p>The secondary mirror must center in the focuser draw tube and angle correctly to reflect the entire primary mirror to the eyepiece. Start in daylight or with room lighting—secondary alignment doesn't require darkness.</p>

          <p><strong>Center the Secondary in the Focuser:</strong> Remove eyepiece and insert sight tube into focuser. Look through sight tube—you should see the secondary mirror centered in the draw tube opening. If it appears off-center, loosen the secondary mirror holder's center bolt (this allows rotation) and gently slide the secondary until it appears centered. Tighten center bolt to lock position. The secondary should appear as a circle (or ellipse in fast systems) precisely centered in the round focuser opening.</p>

          <p><strong>Angle the Secondary Correctly:</strong> Still looking through sight tube, you should now see the primary mirror's reflection centered in the secondary mirror. If the primary appears offset (more secondary edge visible on one side), adjust the secondary's tilt using the three adjustment screws on the secondary holder. Turning a screw clockwise pulls the secondary toward that screw; counterclockwise pushes away. Make small adjustments (1/4 turn), checking after each change. Goal: primary mirror's reflection centered in secondary, with small donut hole (focuser draw tube reflection) centered in primary's reflection.</p>

          <p>Note: In fast focal ratio systems (f/4-f/5), the secondary may appear elliptical rather than circular when viewed down the focuser—this is normal and correct. The secondary must be tilted to catch the fast cone of light from the primary.</p>

          <h3>Step 2: Primary Mirror Alignment (Laser Method)</h3>
          <p>With secondary aligned, now align the primary mirror so it focuses light precisely at the optical axis. This requires the laser collimator.</p>

          <p><strong>Insert Laser Collimator:</strong> Remove sight tube and insert laser collimator into focuser. Turn it on—you'll see red laser dot somewhere on the primary mirror face. The laser beam represents the optical axis; your goal is to adjust the primary so this beam reflects back to illuminate the collimator's entrance target (usually marked with rings or crosshairs).</p>

          <p><strong>Adjust Primary Mirror:</strong> At the rear of the telescope tube, locate three to six collimation bolts (usually Phillips head or hex bolts) arranged in a circle around the primary mirror cell. These bolts push/pull the mirror, changing its tilt. The laser dot on the primary shows current alignment; you need to move this dot until the return beam hits the collimator's target. Strategy: identify which direction the dot needs to move. Tighten the bolt(s) closest to where you want the dot to move; loosen the bolt opposite. Make small adjustments (1/4 turn), checking the laser return after each change. The return beam becomes visible as a red dot on the collimator once you're close—then make fine adjustments until this return dot centers on the collimator's target.</p>

          <p><strong>Final Precision:</strong> When the laser return dot centers on the collimator target, your telescope is collimated. Check by gently rotating the focuser—the laser pattern should remain centered throughout rotation. If it wobbles or shifts, the focuser draw tube may be slightly misaligned (uncommon but possible). Verify collimation with star test (described in star testing section).</p>

          <h3>Step 3: Primary Mirror Alignment (Cheshire Method)</h3>
          <p>The Cheshire eyepiece provides an alternative to laser collimators and is preferred by many experienced observers for final precision.</p>

          <p><strong>Insert Cheshire:</strong> Remove laser and insert Cheshire eyepiece into focuser. Look through the Cheshire's peep sight—you'll see the illuminated optical path with crosshairs marking the optical axis. The 45-degree window illuminates the tube interior, making reflections visible.</p>

          <p><strong>Check Alignment Visually:</strong> Through the Cheshire, you should see concentric circles: the focuser draw tube, the secondary mirror, the primary mirror's reflection in the secondary, and the donut hole (draw tube reflection in primary). If the primary's center mark (usually a small spot or ring at the mirror's center) appears offset from the Cheshire crosshairs, the primary needs adjustment.</p>

          <p><strong>Adjust Primary:</strong> Turn the primary mirror collimation bolts (same as laser method) while viewing through Cheshire. Your goal: center the primary mirror's center mark on the Cheshire crosshairs. Make small adjustments, checking after each change. When the primary center mark appears precisely on the crosshairs, and all reflections appear concentric, collimation is complete.</p>

