          <h2>SCT Collimation: Schmidt-Cassegrain Procedure</h2>
          <p>Schmidt-Cassegrain Telescopes (SCTs) require simpler collimation than Newtonians because only the secondary mirror needs adjustment—the primary remains fixed. SCT collimation involves tilting the secondary mirror (mounted on the corrector plate's interior) using three adjustment screws accessible from the front of the telescope.</p>

          <h3>When to Collimate SCTs</h3>
          <p>Check SCT collimation whenever image quality degrades, after transport or shipping, every few months with regular use, or if star test reveals asymmetric diffraction patterns. Well-mounted SCTs can hold collimation for extended periods—some users collimate only once yearly if the telescope remains permanently on a pier. Frequent transport or temperature extremes increase collimation drift.</p>

          <h3>SCT Collimation Procedure</h3>
          <p><strong>Star Test Setup:</strong> Unlike Newtonians which can be roughly collimated with tools, SCTs require star testing for collimation. Point telescope at bright star (magnitude 1-3) at high altitude (to minimize atmospheric turbulence). Use high magnification (200x-300x). Center star precisely in eyepiece field.</p>

          <p><strong>Defocus and Observe Pattern:</strong> Carefully rack focus out until the star expands into a disk with concentric rings (diffraction pattern). Observe both inside and outside focus (the patterns should mirror each other if collimated). Properly collimated SCTs show perfectly concentric rings centered in the field. Collimation errors appear as: asymmetric rings (elliptical rather than circular), brighter on one side, or with offset center point.</p>

          <p><strong>Identify Adjustment Direction:</strong> Note which direction the pattern appears asymmetric or offset. The secondary mirror needs to tilt toward the dimmer or smaller side of the pattern. For example, if rings appear compressed on the left and expanded on the right, the secondary needs to tilt left.</p>

          <p><strong>Adjust Secondary Screws:</strong> At the front of the telescope, locate three small Phillips head or hex screws arranged in a triangle around the corrector plate (secondary mirror attaches to the corrector's rear surface). Use appropriate screwdriver or 2mm Allen key. To tilt the secondary in a specific direction: turn one screw clockwise (tightening) while turning the opposite screw counterclockwise (loosening). This shifts secondary position without changing the spacing dramatically. Make VERY small adjustments—1/8 to 1/4 turn maximum.</p>

          <p><strong>Re-test and Iterate:</strong> Return to star test after each adjustment. The diffraction pattern should move toward symmetry. Continue making small adjustments and testing until patterns appear perfectly concentric both inside and outside focus. Patience required—SCT collimation often demands 3-4 iterations of adjustment and testing.</p>

          <h3>SCT Collimation Tips</h3>
          <p>Work on nights with steady seeing (stars not twinkling severely)—atmospheric turbulence obscures diffraction patterns making collimation assessment difficult. Use bright stars but not too bright—magnitude 1-2 ideal; magnitude 0 or planets often too bright causing glare. Make very small adjustments—SCTs are sensitive and 1/4 turn can dramatically change collimation. Some SCT models (particularly Celestron) have spring-loaded secondary screws—maintain spring tension by never loosening all three screws simultaneously. If collimation gets severely off, consult manufacturer's reset procedure before attempting adjustment. Consider marking screw positions with paint pen before starting so you can return to original positions if needed.</p>

