        <section id="mirror-cleaning" class="content-section">
          <h2>Mirror Cleaning: Safe Techniques for Delicate Coatings</h2>
          <p>Telescope mirrors sport delicate aluminum or silver coatings just nanometers thick—improper cleaning easily scratches these coatings, causing permanent light scatter and contrast reduction far worse than the dust you're trying to remove. The cardinal rule: clean mirrors only when absolutely necessary, and when you do clean, use ultra-gentle techniques prioritizing coating protection over removing every dust speck.</p>

          <h3>When to Clean (and When to Leave Alone)</h3>
          <p><strong>DON'T Clean:</strong> A few dozen dust specks or particles scattered across the mirror surface cause negligible performance degradation—these tiny particles occupy perhaps 0.001% of the mirror's collecting area and remain completely invisible in observed images. Even a moderately dusty mirror (hundreds of particles) performs nearly identically to pristine optics. Resist the urge to clean for dust alone.</p>

          <p><strong>DO Clean:</strong> Heavy dust accumulation covering >5% of mirror surface. Fingerprints or skin oils on mirror face (these can etch coatings if left long-term). Water spots or dried dew residue creating visible marks. Atmospheric pollutants or automotive residue forming films. Fungus growth appearing as white threads or spots (requires immediate cleaning). Generally: if mirror looks dirty to naked eye in bright light, cleaning warranted; if it looks clean except under close inspection with flashlight, leave it alone.</p>

          <p>Many experienced observers clean primary mirrors only every 2-5 years despite regular use. Secondary mirrors typically need even less frequent cleaning due to smaller surface area. Every cleaning risks coating damage, so the less frequently you clean, the longer your coatings last (typical aluminum coating lasts 10-20 years with gentle care; aggressive cleaning can reduce this to 5-10 years).</p>

          <h3>Gentle Cleaning Method: Rinse and Soak</h3>
          <p>This safest technique removes most contamination without touching the coating. Suitable for routine cleaning of moderately dirty mirrors.</p>

          <p><strong>Step 1 - Remove Mirror:</strong> Disassemble telescope carefully, removing primary mirror from cell. Note mirror orientation (mark with tape if no existing marker) so you can reinstall in same position, preserving collimation. Handle mirror by edges only, never touching the coated face. Work on soft towels to prevent drops from damaging mirror. Secondary mirrors often don't need removal for cleaning—clean in place if possible.</p>

          <p><strong>Step 2 - Initial Rinse:</strong> Hold mirror at 30-degree angle under gentle stream of room-temperature distilled water (NOT tap water—minerals leave deposits). Let water flow across surface for 30-60 seconds, floating away loose dust particles. Never wipe at this stage—dry dust particles scratch coatings. Goal: remove 80-90% of loose contamination through gentle water flow alone.</p>

          <p><strong>Step 3 - Prepare Cleaning Solution:</strong> Fill clean container (larger than mirror) with room-temperature distilled water. Add 2-3 drops of Dawn dish soap (original blue formula—no lotions, moisturizers, or antibacterial agents). Mix gently without creating suds. This mild solution breaks down oils and films without harming aluminum coatings. Commercial mirror cleaning solutions also work well ($15-$20).</p>

          <p><strong>Step 4 - Soak:</strong> Submerge mirror face-up in cleaning solution. Let soak 2-5 minutes allowing solution to dissolve oils and loosen particles. For heavily soiled mirrors, gently agitate water to increase cleaning action. No scrubbing or wiping—let chemistry do the work.</p>

          <p><strong>Step 5 - Rinse Thoroughly:</strong> Remove mirror and rinse under distilled water for 60 seconds, ensuring all soap residue washes away. Soap residue dries to visible film, so thorough rinsing critical. Tilt mirror to encourage water drainage. Final rinse with deionized water if available (even purer than distilled).</p>

          <p><strong>Step 6 - Dry:</strong> Stand mirror on edge on soft towel in dust-free area (bathroom after hot shower creates humid, dust-settled air). Let air dry completely—this takes 30-60 minutes. NEVER wipe with cloth, paper, or compressed air. If water spots form despite distilled water rinse, gently dab (don't wipe) with lint-free optical tissue, or accept the spots (they're harmless).</p>

          <h3>Deep Cleaning Method: Cotton Ball Technique</h3>
          <p>For stubborn residue (sticky sap, bug debris, dried water spots) that won't rinse away, ultra-gentle contact cleaning becomes necessary. Use extreme caution.</p>

          <p><strong>Supplies:</strong> Large bag of 100% cotton balls (cosmetic puffs, not cotton-tipped swabs), Dawn dish soap or commercial mirror cleaner, distilled water, very soft towel. Never use: paper products (tissues, paper towels), cloth (microfiber or otherwise), compressed air, or solvents (alcohol, acetone, glass cleaner).</p>

          <p><strong>Technique:</strong> After initial rinse (removing all dry dust), soak cotton ball in cleaning solution until saturated. Hold cotton ball between thumb and forefinger with minimum pressure. Drag cotton ball straight across mirror in single direction (NOT circular motions). Lift cotton ball off mirror at end of stroke—never drag back across previously cleaned area. Discard used cotton ball; get fresh cotton ball for next stroke. Continue with fresh cotton balls and single-direction strokes until entire mirror cleaned. Each cotton ball gets ONE stroke maximum—this prevents scratching from particles picked up during the stroke.</p>

          <p><strong>Rinse and Dry:</strong> After cotton ball cleaning, rinse thoroughly with distilled water (60+ seconds) to remove all soap. Air dry completely standing on edge.</p>

          <div class="info-box glass">
            <h3>Mirror Cleaning Golden Rules</h3>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Clean infrequently:</strong> Once every 2-5 years for most users. Dust is better than scratches.</li>
              <li><strong>Never wipe dry dust:</strong> Always rinse away dust particles with distilled water first.</li>
              <li><strong>Use distilled water only:</strong> Tap water minerals leave deposits.</li>
              <li><strong>Single-direction strokes:</strong> Never circular motions or back-and-forth wiping.</li>
              <li><strong>Fresh cotton ball per stroke:</strong> Prevents scratching from picked-up particles.</li>
              <li><strong>Air dry completely:</strong> Never wipe dry—causes scratches.</li>
              <li><strong>When in doubt, send out:</strong> Professional cleaning ($50-$100) safer for expensive optics.</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>

