        <section id="dew-prevention" class="content-section">
          <h2>Dew Prevention: Keeping Optics Clear</h2>
          <p>Dew formation on telescope optics ruins observing sessions by coating objective lenses, corrector plates, eyepieces, and finder scopes with moisture that scatters light and prevents imaging. Understanding dew formation mechanisms and prevention techniques keeps optics clear during humid nights that defeat unprepared observers.</p>

          <h3>Why Dew Forms on Telescope Optics</h3>
          <p>Dew forms when surface temperature drops below the dew point—the temperature at which air becomes saturated and water vapor condenses into liquid droplets. Telescope optics radiate heat to the night sky, cooling below ambient air temperature. On humid nights (relative humidity &gt;70%), this radiative cooling quickly drops optics below dew point, triggering condensation. Objective lenses and corrector plates, exposed directly to cold sky, cool fastest and dew first. Eyepieces and finder scopes follow. Open-tube Dobsonians suffer less dewing than sealed-tube refractors and SCTs because primary mirrors sit deep in tubes with less sky exposure.</p>

          <p>Dew risk increases with: high humidity (&gt;70% RH), clear skies (clouds block radiative cooling), calm winds (prevents air mixing), and cold nights (lower dew point). Coastal locations, nights after rain, and fall/spring seasons create prime dewing conditions. Desert and winter observations typically stay dew-free due to low humidity.</p>

          <h3>Passive Dew Prevention</h3>
          <p><strong>Dew Shields:</strong> Extended tubes or baffles projecting forward from the objective block radiant cooling while allowing light to enter. A dew shield 1.5x to 2x the objective diameter and extending beyond the optics by at least the diameter helps significantly. Most refractors and SCTs benefit from aftermarket dew shields ($30-$80). DIY dew shields from craft foam, poster board, or flexible plastics work well—line interior with black felt to reduce stray light. Dew shields also improve contrast by blocking stray light from entering the optical path.</p>

          <p><strong>Lens Caps Until Ready:</strong> Keep objective covers on until you begin observing. This prevents optics from cooling unnecessarily before use. During breaks (waiting for clouds to pass, chatting with fellow observers), replace covers to maintain temperature. This simple technique prevents dew formation during idle periods.</p>

          <p><strong>Strategic Tube Positioning:</strong> Point telescope away from cool portions of sky when not actively observing. Horizontal positioning exposes optics to warmer ground-level air rather than cold sky, reducing radiative cooling. Some observers park scopes pointing downward or horizontally between observations.</p>

          <h3>Active Dew Prevention: Dew Heaters</h3>
          <p>Dew heaters wrap around objectives, corrector plates, eyepieces, and finder scopes, maintaining temperatures above dew point through gentle electrical heating. These represent the most reliable dew prevention for challenging conditions.</p>

          <p><strong>Dew Heater Strips:</strong> Flexible resistance heaters with velcro or elastic straps secure around telescope tube near optics. Typical power: 5-15 watts depending on aperture size. Larger apertures require more wattage (8" SCT needs ~12W; 4" refractor needs ~6W). Quality strips cost $30-$60; complete systems with controller $100-$150. Popular brands: Kendrick, Dew-Not, Thousand Oaks.</p>

          <p><strong>Power Systems:</strong> Dew heaters require 12V DC power. Options include portable 12V batteries ($30-$60), power banks with 12V output ($40-$80), or AC-to-12V power supplies if observing near outlets. Battery capacity needed depends on session length and heater wattage—typical 7Ah battery runs 12W heater for 6-7 hours. Calculate runtime: battery amp-hours / heater amps (watts/12V).</p>

          <p><strong>Dew Heater Controllers:</strong> Adjustable controllers ($40-$80) let you dial in minimum heating needed, extending battery life and preventing excessive heat that can create air currents degrading image quality. Start with low power; increase only if dew forms. Use just enough heat to prevent dew—not maximum heat.</p>

          <p><strong>Eyepiece and Finder Heaters:</strong> Smaller dew heater strips ($15-$25 each) wrap around eyepieces and finder scopes. These low-wattage heaters (2-4W) operate from same 12V system as objective heaters. Eyepiece dewing often occurs later in sessions than objective dewing, so you can add eyepiece heaters mid-session if needed.</p>

          <h3>Dealing with Dew Formation</h3>
          <p>If dew forms despite precautions: Never wipe optics while dewed—this smears moisture and may scratch coatings. Instead, apply gentle heat using hair dryer on low setting held 30cm from optics, or temporarily increase dew heater power to evaporate moisture. Once optics dry, maintain higher heater power to prevent recurrence. For eyepieces, body heat from hands often suffices—cup eyepiece in palms for 30 seconds. Severely dewed optics may require 5-10 minutes with heat to fully dry.</p>

          <p>After dewing episodes, check optics after session ends. Most dew evaporates cleanly leaving no residue. If water spots remain, gently rinse with distilled water and air dry—don't let minerals from dew (which often contains atmospheric pollutants) etch into coatings.</p>
