          <h2>Storage Best Practices: Protecting Your Investment</h2>
          <p>Proper storage preserves telescope optical and mechanical quality for decades while preventing damage from moisture, dust, temperature extremes, and fungus. Where and how you store equipment between observing sessions dramatically impacts long-term condition and performance.</p>

          <h3>Ideal Storage Environment</h3>
          <p><strong>Temperature and Humidity:</strong> Store in climate-controlled indoor spaces maintaining 15-25°C (60-75°F) with 30-50% relative humidity. Avoid locations with extreme temperature swings (attics, garages, sheds) which cause thermal stress, expand/contract optical cements, and promote condensation. Avoid very humid environments (&gt;70% RH) promoting fungus growth, or very dry conditions (&lt;20% RH) potentially drying optical cements.</p>

          <p><strong>Clean, Dust-Free Space:</strong> Indoor closets, spare bedrooms, or dedicated observatory storage beats garages or basements (often dusty, humid). Dust accumulation on optics necessitates cleaning, which risks coating damage. Well-sealed storage cases mitigate dusty environments, but starting with clean air ideal.</p>

          <p><strong>Dark Storage:</strong> Avoid prolonged direct sunlight exposure—UV radiation degrades rubber armoring, plastic components, and optical cements over years. Dark closets or covered storage prevents UV damage.</p>

          <h3>Storage Cases and Covers</h3>
          <p><strong>Hard Cases:</strong> Protect telescopes during storage and transport. Options include original manufacturer cases (often included with premium equipment), Pelican cases ($100-$400 depending on size, excellent protection), aluminum camera cases ($60-$150), or padded rolling cases ($80-$200). Cases should include foam padding preventing movement during transport, weather-resistant seals, and room for accessories.</p>

          <p><strong>Soft Cases:</strong> Padded nylon or canvas bags ($40-$120) protect from dust and minor bumps but offer minimal impact protection. Suitable for storage and gentle transport (car trunk to observing site) but not airline travel or rough handling. Many include straps for accessories like eyepieces, finder scopes, and power supplies.</p>

          <p><strong>Dust Covers:</strong> For telescopes stored in open positions (Dobsonians on platforms, permanent observatory mounts), dust covers prevent particle accumulation. Commercial shrouds ($30-$80) or DIY solutions (bed sheets, painter's drop cloths) work equally well. Ensure covers breathe (don't seal telescopes in plastic bags or vapor barriers promoting condensation).</p>

          <h3>Humidity Control: Desiccants</h3>
          <p>Controlling humidity in storage cases prevents fungus growth on optics and corrosion on metal components. Include desiccant packets in closed storage cases.</p>

          <p><strong>Silica Gel Packets:</strong> Reusable desiccant beads absorbing moisture from air. Include 50-100g silica gel per medium case (telescopes up to 8"). Color-indicating silica gel changes from blue/orange to pink/green when saturated with moisture, signaling regeneration needed. Regenerate by heating in 120°C (250°F) oven for 2-3 hours, returning beads to dry state. Available at camera stores or online ($10-$15 per pound).</p>

          <p><strong>Alternative Desiccants:</strong> Dry rice works as cheap desiccant for short-term storage (place 1 cup rice in breathable cloth bag in case). Rechargeable desiccant canisters ($15-$25) include built-in indicators and plug into wall outlet for regeneration.</p>

          <p><strong>Monitoring Humidity:</strong> Small hygrometers ($10-$15) placed in storage cases let you verify desiccant effectiveness. Target 30-50% RH for optics storage. Replace or regenerate desiccant every 3-6 months depending on ambient humidity.</p>

          <h3>Storage Positioning and Accessories</h3>
          <p><strong>Optical Positioning:</strong> Store telescopes with optics horizontal or angled downward, never pointing upward. Upward-facing optics collect falling dust. Dobsonians store well in normal altitude-azimuth position. Refractors and SCTs can lie horizontally or angle downward at 45 degrees.</p>

          <p><strong>Caps and Covers:</strong> Always install objective caps and eyepiece caps before storage. This basic practice prevents 90% of dust accumulation on optical surfaces. Ensure caps fit securely—loose caps fall off during storage.</p>

          <p><strong>Eyepiece Storage:</strong> Store eyepieces in dedicated cases with individual compartments preventing lens-to-lens contact. Plastic compartment boxes ($15-$30) or padded cases ($30-$80) work well. Include desiccant in eyepiece cases. Install caps on both ends of each eyepiece.</p>

          <p><strong>Battery Removal:</strong> Remove batteries from GoTo hand controllers, red dot finders, and dew heater controllers before storage. Batteries leak over time, corroding electronics. Store batteries separately in battery cases or original packaging.</p>

          <h3>Long-Term Storage (Months to Years)</h3>
          <p>For telescopes stored long-term without use: Perform thorough cleaning and inspection before storage to address any developing issues. Apply light oil to mechanical components (focuser gears, mount axes) preventing corrosion. Double-wrap in dust covers or store in sealed containers with ample desiccant. Check every 3-6 months for fungus development, desiccant saturation, and mechanical condition. Inspect for pest intrusion (mice, insects) which can damage cases and optics. Before returning to service after long storage, recollimate, inspect optics for fungus, and verify mechanical components operate smoothly.</p>
