        <section id="maintenance-schedule" class="content-section">
          <h2>Comprehensive Maintenance Schedule</h2>
          <p>Following systematic maintenance schedules ensures nothing gets overlooked while preventing over-maintenance (excessive cleaning damages coatings faster than dust). Adjust frequency based on usage intensity, storage conditions, and local environment.</p>

          <h3>Before Every Observing Session (Pre-Flight Check)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Newtonian Collimation Check:</strong> Perform quick star test or laser check; adjust if needed (3-5 minutes)</li>
            <li><strong>Optical Inspection:</strong> Visually examine objective, eyepieces, finder for dew, frost, or major dust; wipe eyepieces if smudged</li>
            <li><strong>Finder Alignment:</strong> Verify finder aligned with main scope; adjust if misaligned from transport</li>
            <li><strong>Mechanical Check:</strong> Test focuser smooth operation; ensure mount axes move freely; verify tripod legs lock securely</li>
            <li><strong>Power Check:</strong> If using GoTo system or dew heaters, verify batteries charged or power supply functional</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>After Every Observing Session (Post-Session Care)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Dew Check:</strong> Inspect optics for dew or frost; if present, allow air drying before capping or use gentle heat source</li>
            <li><strong>Cap Installation:</strong> Install objective caps and eyepiece caps before packing equipment</li>
            <li><strong>Condensation Prevention:</strong> If telescope warm from indoor storage used in cold outdoor air, allow temperature equalization in unheated space (garage) before returning to warm indoor storage; this prevents condensation</li>
            <li><strong>Brief Inspection:</strong> Check for any damage, loose components, or issues developed during session</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Monthly Maintenance (Frequent Users)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Deep Optical Inspection:</strong> Use flashlight at angle to inspect primary and secondary mirrors for dust accumulation; assess if cleaning becoming necessary</li>
            <li><strong>Eyepiece Cleaning:</strong> Clean eyepiece lenses using lens cleaning solution and microfiber cloth if visibly smudged or dusty</li>
            <li><strong>Focuser Lubrication:</strong> If focuser feels tight or gritty, apply light machine oil to rack gears; wipe excess; test smooth operation</li>
            <li><strong>Mount Inspection:</strong> Verify all mount bolts tight; check for any looseness in altitude or azimuth axes; tighten as needed</li>
            <li><strong>Finder Maintenance:</strong> Clean finder objective and eyepiece; verify finder bracket secure; replace batteries if using illuminated reticle</li>
            <li><strong>SCT Collimation Check:</strong> Perform star test; adjust if pattern shows asymmetry (every 1-3 months depending on use)</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Annual Maintenance (All Telescopes)</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Mirror Cleaning Assessment:</strong> Inspect primary and secondary mirrors in bright light; clean if dust coverage >5% of surface or if fingerprints, water spots, or films present (most telescopes don't need annual cleaning—every 2-5 years more typical)</li>
            <li><strong>Spider Vane Inspection (Newtonians):</strong> Check spider vanes for looseness; tighten screws if vanes shift under light finger pressure</li>
            <li><strong>Primary Mirror Clips:</strong> Verify clips not over-tightened (should allow slight mirror movement); loosen 1/4 turn if clips very tight</li>
            <li><strong>Mount Lubrication:</strong> Clean and re-grease mount axes using telescope-appropriate lubricant (lithium grease for manual mounts, specified lubricant for GoTo systems)</li>
            <li><strong>Electronics Check:</strong> Inspect all electronic components for corrosion; clean contacts with electronics contact cleaner; verify hand controllers and motors functional</li>
            <li><strong>Structural Inspection:</strong> Check tube assembly for cracks, loose screws, damaged components; verify mirror cells secure; inspect focuser assembly</li>
            <li><strong>Desiccant Replacement:</strong> Replace or regenerate all desiccant packets in storage cases</li>
            <li><strong>Accessory Maintenance:</strong> Clean all eyepieces; inspect cases for damage; organize and inventory accessories; replace worn straps or damaged components</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>As-Needed Maintenance</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Collimation:</strong> Whenever star test shows degradation or after transport (Newtonians); every few months to yearly (SCTs)</li>
            <li><strong>Mirror Cleaning:</strong> Only when dust severe (>5% coverage), fingerprints present, or water spots visible</li>
            <li><strong>Finder Alignment:</strong> After any transport or if finder shows misalignment during use</li>
            <li><strong>Battery Replacement:</strong> When GoTo controllers show low battery warnings or finders dim</li>
            <li><strong>Dew Shield Repair:</strong> If torn or damaged; DIY replacement easy and inexpensive</li>
            <li><strong>Cable Replacement:</strong> If power cables show damage, fraying, or unreliable connections</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="info-box glass">
            <h3>Maintenance Time Investment</h3>
            <p><strong>Pre-session:</strong> 5-10 minutes (mostly collimation check for Newtonians)</p>
            <p><strong>Post-session:</strong> 5 minutes (capping, dew check)</p>
            <p><strong>Monthly:</strong> 30-45 minutes (deep inspection, focuser lube, cleaning)</p>
            <p><strong>Annual:</strong> 2-3 hours (deep cleaning, lubrication, full inspection)</p>
            <p><strong>Total yearly:</strong> ~10 hours for frequently-used equipment—minimal investment protecting hundreds to thousands of dollars of equipment</p>
          </div>
