        <section id="troubleshooting" class="content-section">
          <h2>Troubleshooting Common Problems</h2>
          <p>Telescope problems generally fall into optical issues (image quality), mechanical issues (movement and focus), or collimation problems. Systematic diagnosis identifies causes and solutions.</p>

          <h3>Optical Quality Problems</h3>
          <p><strong>Soft, Mushy Images:</strong> <em>Possible causes:</em> Poor collimation (Newtonians/SCTs), atmospheric turbulence, poor seeing conditions, mirror not temperature-stabilized, pinched optics, dew on optics. <em>Solutions:</em> Check collimation via star test—adjust if needed. Verify telescope reached ambient temperature (cool-down time: 30-60 minutes for medium scopes, 60-90 minutes for large scopes). Check for dew on objective or corrector plate—dry if present. Test on different nights to rule out atmospheric conditions. Inspect for pinched optics via star test; loosen mirror clips if six-pointed pattern visible.</p>

          <p><strong>Asymmetric Star Images:</strong> <em>Possible causes:</em> Collimation error, astigmatism in optics or eyepiece, focuser drawtube misalignment. <em>Solutions:</em> Perform star test—asymmetric diffraction rings indicate collimation problem; adjust per collimation procedures. Test with different eyepieces—if problem persists across all eyepieces, likely mirror collimation; if only one eyepiece, eyepiece defect. Check focuser alignment by rotating focuser while viewing star—if star image orbits or wobbles, focuser misaligned (uncommon but requires professional service).</p>

          <p><strong>Reduced Contrast:</strong> <em>Possible causes:</em> Dust on optics, dirty eyepieces, degraded optical coatings, dew film, stray light entering optical path. <em>Solutions:</em> Clean eyepieces (easier than mirrors). Inspect mirror coatings for deterioration—old coatings (15+ years) may show patches or discoloration; recoating required ($150-$300 professional service). Check for dew film—even invisible moisture films scatter light. Use dew shield to block stray light from streetlights, Moon, or other sources.</p>

          <p><strong>Double or Triple Star Images:</strong> <em>Possible causes:</em> Severe collimation error, damaged optical components, internal reflections from dust on eyepiece or diagonal. <em>Solutions:</em> Check collimation—severe misalignment can create ghost images. Clean eyepiece and diagonal surfaces. Inspect for cracks or damage to optical elements. If problem persists after collimation and cleaning, optical damage likely requires professional assessment.</p>

          <h3>Mechanical Problems</h3>
          <p><strong>Stiff or Binding Focuser:</strong> <em>Causes:</em> Dried lubricant, debris in rack-and-pinion mechanism, over-tightened focuser lock. <em>Solutions:</em> Ensure focuser lock (tension adjustment) not over-tightened. Clean focuser mechanism: remove eyepiece, inspect for debris or old grease. Apply light machine oil to rack gears. Work focuser through full range of travel to distribute lubricant. Wipe excess oil. If still stiff, partial disassembly and cleaning may be needed (consult manufacturer instructions).</p>

          <p><strong>Wobbly or Loose Focuser:</strong> <em>Causes:</em> Worn focuser bearings, loose mounting screws, insufficient focuser tension. <em>Solutions:</em> Tighten focuser mounting screws (typically 4-6 screws securing focuser to tube). Increase focuser tension using tension adjustment knob if available. For worn focusers with excessive play, replacement may be needed ($80-$200 for aftermarket focusers depending on size and quality).</p>

          <p><strong>Mount Slipping or Drifting:</strong> <em>Causes:</em> Loose mounting bolts, worn friction pads, insufficient counterbalance weight. <em>Solutions:</em> Tighten all mount bolts and screws. Adjust altitude and azimuth friction to appropriate levels—should move smoothly with moderate force but not drift under telescope weight. Add counterweights if telescope tube-heavy. For Dobsonians, replace worn Teflon pads ($15-$30) or add altitude brakes.</p>

          <p><strong>GoTo Not Tracking Accurately:</strong> <em>Causes:</em> Poor alignment (star alignment), polar alignment error (EQ mounts), mechanical backlash, low battery power, firmware issues. <em>Solutions:</em> Perform careful 2-star or 3-star alignment following manufacturer procedure precisely. Verify bubble level on mount base showing level surface. Check battery voltage—low batteries cause erratic tracking. Calibrate backlash compensation per mount manual. Update firmware if manufacturer released new version addressing tracking issues.</p>

          <h3>Collimation-Specific Problems</h3>
          <p><strong>Can't Achieve Collimation Despite Adjustments:</strong> <em>Possible causes:</em> Focuser drawtube misalignment, laser collimator itself miscollimated, secondary holder bent or damaged, primary mirror cell warped. <em>Solutions:</em> Verify laser collimator accuracy by rotating it in focuser—laser dot should stay stationary; if dot orbits, laser itself miscollimated (return for replacement or recalibration). Switch to Cheshire eyepiece method eliminating laser variability. Inspect secondary holder for visible damage or asymmetry. Check primary mirror cell for warping or cracks. Severe mechanical damage may require replacement parts.</p>

          <p><strong>Collimation Doesn't Hold:</strong> <em>Causes:</em> Loose collimation screws, worn spring tension, flexure in tube or mirror cell, vibration during transport. <em>Solutions:</em> After achieving good collimation, verify all collimation screws snug (not over-tight, just firm). Check spring tension on collimation bolts—weak springs can't hold adjustment. Ensure mirror cell mounted firmly to tube (no flexure or play). Transport telescope carefully avoiding vibration and impacts. Consider locking collimation with blue (removable) thread-locker on screws after achieving perfect collimation (allows future adjustment but resists vibration).</p>

